    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Give and Take on Napster</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Tom King letter on June 29 article on Napster says the ability to control music distribution as we know it is over and the music industry will have to adapt</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is time the music industry realized that the world has changed. Licenses become obsolete when the ability to recreate becomes readily available.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is time the music industry realized that the world has changed. Licenses become obsolete when the ability to recreate becomes readily available.</p>
        <p>With the Internet and the ability to copy digitally, the ability to control music distribution has ceased as we know it. The music industry will continue to make money but not by selling the product itself. The future lies in providing value-added to the music and linking downloads and plays to advertising.</p>
        <p>TOM KING  New York City</p>
      </block>
